node.text:
Tap on Link in Bio to read the full guide!

Summer in Iceland is wonderful. The days are long and the nights are as bright as days. Here are a few tips on how to best enjoy it.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Iceland Explore on August 24, 2021. May be an image of ‎waterfall and ‎text that says '‎)ه @iceland. @iceland.explore DID YOU KNOW THAT ICELAND WAS THE LAST PLACE ON EARTH TO BE SETTLED BY HUMANS Save the best for last? Iceland is known as one of the youngest landmasses on the planet and was one of the last places on earth to be settled by humans. Surprisingly, over 1, 100 years ago Vikings from Norway discovered Iceland by accident.‎'‎‎.

node.text:
Which of these facts you didn’t know about?

Visit LINK in our Bio to learn more about #iceland

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Iceland Explore on August 24, 2021. May be an image of ‎waterfall and ‎text that says '‎)ه @iceland. @iceland.explore DID YOU KNOW THAT ICELAND WAS THE LAST PLACE ON EARTH TO BE SETTLED BY HUMANS Save the best for last? Iceland is known as one of the youngest landmasses on the planet and was one of the last places on earth to be settled by humans. Surprisingly, over 1, 100 years ago Vikings from Norway discovered Iceland by accident.‎'‎‎.

Photo by Iceland Explore on August 24, 2021. May be an image of bottle and text that says '@iceland.explore DID YOU KNOW THAT BEER WAS BANNED IN ICELAND A century ago, Iceland banned all alcoholic drinks. Within a decade, red wine had been legalised, followed by spirits in the 1930s. But full-strength beer remained off-limits until March 1989. When full prohibition became law 100 years ago, alcohol in general was frowned upon, and beer was especially out of favour- for political reasons.'.

Photo by Iceland Explore on August 24, 2021. May be an image of riding on a horse and text that says '@iceland.explore DID YOU KNOW THE MEANING OF THE ICELANDIC FLAG? Icelanders see it nowadays. To them, the white stands for the glaciers and snow, the blue for the mountains and the red for the island's volcanoes. Originally though, the red was added to symbolize Christianity. This has not stuck in the mind of Icelanders who are more likely to link with volcanoes and magma. The flag became the National flag when Iceland gained its independence from Denmark in 1918.'.

Photo by Iceland Explore on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says '@iceland.explore DID YOU KNOW THAT ABOUT 11% OF ICELAND IS COVERED BY GLACIERS Glaciers form Earth largest reservoir of fresh water. Iceland's glaciers store around twenty times the country' average annual precipitation. Were they to melt, the water would cause the global sea level to rise around 1 cm. Glaciers are the source for all major rivers in Iceland. Meltwater from glaciers accounts for around a third of the water that flows into the ocean annually in Iceland.'.
Photo by Iceland Explore in Iceland with @kevin._.pages. May be an image of body of water and nature.
